message.content: The theorem states that for any function $G : \mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{R}$, the function $G$ tends to $0$ in the neighborhood sense as its inputs tend to infinity.
The theorem states that for every function $G$ from the real numbers to the real numbers, the function $G$ tends to $0$ in the neighborhood filter at $+\infty$.
The theorem states that for any function $G: \mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{R}$, the function $G$ tends toward 0 as its input approaches infinity.
The theorem states that for any function $G: \mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{R}$, $G(x)$ tends to $0$ as $x$ approaches infinity.
The theorem states that for every function \( G: \mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{R} \), as the input approaches infinity, \( G \) tends to 0 in the neighborhood topology of 0.
For any function $G: \mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{R}$, as its argument tends to infinity, $G(x)$ converges to $0$.
The theorem states that for any real-valued function $G$, the function does not necessarily tend to $0$ as the input approaches infinity.

The theorem states that for every real-valued function $G$, as the input tends to $\infty$ (in the filter sense of `Filter.atTop`), the output of $G$ tends to $0$ in the neighborhood filter sense (`nhds 0`).
The theorem states that for every function $G : \mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{R}$, the function $G$ tends to 0 in the neighborhood filter as its argument approaches infinity.
The theorem states that for every function $G: \mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{R}$, $G$ tends to $0$ in the neighborhood filter as $G$ tends to infinity.
